(Correction
    "Names do not carry their full ancestry. Enclosing crate, channel, module, type, and field context already supply meaning, so child names should not repeat every ancestor noun. Inside Spirit, intent is the domain; inside Entry, fields are already entry fields."
    "Do you understand how to name things now? Can you give me a breakdown of all your data types? Just get all your data types out of the contracts and let me see them. I want to see what you're doing and let me see if you understand how you need to name things properly. If you understand context, like as in these data types are in the context of being in this repository, this crate, right? This rest crate. They don't need to be like named all the way to the fucking sky. We understand they're from the signal spirit persona. So like the context tells us enough. This is about intent. And what's more is that once there is a basic containing type, let's say intent, there's an intent. Well, all the fields in that struct don't need to say that they're intent. They're fields in the intent struct. Like, you don't rename everything as things get encapsulated. They are implicitly of that encapsulation. They don't need to be renamed after all of their ancestors. You know, if I held the name of all my ancestors, I would be speaking until I die before I could spell my name out."
    "Generalizing the persona-spirit naming correction into the cross-workspace naming rule. Repeated intent wording is intentionally logged again rather than deduplicated because repeated phrasing reinforces the intent and preserves distinct verbatim evidence."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T15:46:23Z)

(Decision
    "Strengthen the no-abbreviations stance across all coding-related guidance files. The current exception list in skills/naming.md is too liberal — psyche pushed back: identifier is always better than id, and CPU is borderline (allowed only because it has become English). Default to spelling out; reach for the acronym exception sparingly. Most code-side shortenings (ctx, cfg, addr, db, tok, buf, ui) are convenience abbreviations, not English words; they belong in the offender table, not the exception list."
    "we don't allow abbreviations for almost anything except maybe ID, but even then identifier is actually better. So I don't, I wouldn't even say we allow ID. Maybe CPU. Okay. Like maybe, but only because it's become sort of part of the English language."
    "Tightening the abbreviation rule beyond what skills/naming.md currently encodes. Psyche's mood is 'almost nothing'; the wider acronym list of 13 items is too generous. Apply by removing id from the exception list, adding a leading caution that most short forms don't qualify, and reaffirming the spelled form is the default."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:20:00Z)

(Decision
    "Both load-bearing naming rules — full-English-words AND no-redundant-ancestor-context — must land in every coding-related guidance file with comparable emphasis, so agents pick up both together as a pair. The two rules pull in opposite directions; they only work together. ESSENCE.md needs a Naming section (AGENTS.md already references one as §'Naming' but the section does not exist). The redundant-ancestor rule, recently generalised from the persona-spirit Entry-not-IntentEntry correction, should be paired with the no-abbreviations rule everywhere."
    "let's make this clear in all the guidance files that are concerned"
    "Manifestation directive: bring the two naming rules together across coding skills. ESSENCE.md §Naming is the missing keystone (AGENTS.md's hard override references it as if it exists). skills/naming.md already carries both rules but with the abbreviation exception list too wide; skills/contract-repo.md and skills/rust-discipline.md carry partial coverage. All need the paired emphasis."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:20:00Z)
